  "texts": [
    "Such problems can be mathematically described by the controversial properties of a geometric shape with the deeply religious name ''Gabriel's Horn'', also known as \"Torricelli's Trumpet\" (Fig. 1).Gabriel's horn is a geometric shape that has the paradoxical property of having infinite surface area but finite volume.",
    "It is formed by rotating the curve y = 1 ⁄ₓ around the x-axis from x = 1 to infinity [17].",
    "The geometrical structure of the horn reveals a fundamental limitation of mathematical calculus when applied to infinite shapes.",
    "While the idea of ignoring infinitesimal pieces works elegantly for finite shapes, it fails completely when dealing with infinity.",
    "But why does this happen?The assumption that allows one to calculate volumes of finite shapes using derivatives and integrals (practically infinitesimal bits can be ignored) seems to be the root cause of the paradox."
  ],
